  "prompt": "If India was a part of UNSC would it have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support?",
  "response": "Yes, if India were a permanent member of the UNSC, it would have been able to ban Masood Azhar without China's support, *provided it could secure the necessary votes from the other members.*\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Permanent Member Veto:**  As a permanent member, India would have the power to veto any UNSC resolution against its interests. However, the power to veto does not mean the power to pass a resolution single-handedly.\n\n*   **Resolution Process:** Banning Masood Azhar requires a UNSC resolution, specifically under the 1267 sanctions regime.  To pass, a resolution needs 9 votes in favor *and* no veto from any of the permanent members (China, France, Russia, the United Kingdom, and the United States).\n\n*   **Scenario with India as a Permanent Member:**\n    *   India, as a permanent member, would vote in favor of banning Masood Azhar.\n    *   Without China's veto, the resolution would pass *if* at least 8 other members of the UNSC also voted in favor.\n    *   If China still opposed the ban, it would need to convince at least 6 other non-permanent members to vote against the resolution or abstain to prevent the required 9 votes.\n\nIn essence, India's presence as a permanent member would shift the dynamic. Instead of China blocking the resolution with a veto, the onus would be on China to garner enough support *from other UNSC members* to prevent the resolution from passing. This is a much more difficult proposition.\n\n**In summary, becoming a permanent member wouldn't guarantee the ban on Masood Azhar, but it would significantly increase the likelihood by removing China's veto power on the issue.** India would still need to engage in diplomacy to secure the necessary votes, but it would be a much stronger position than the one it currently occupies.",
